It is usually presumed that Alice and Bob hold sifted keys x and y, two n-bit strings that are outcomes of X and Y. During reconciliation, Alice and Bob communicate a set of messages M to reconcile their keys. At the end of the protocol, they agree on a shared secret key in the presence of Eve while revealing some information. Therefore, X and Y can be considered correlated random variables, and y is given by transition probability Ì†µÌ±ÉÌ†µÌ±ÉÌ†µÌ±ÉÌ†µÌ†µÌ±ÉÌ±äÌ†µÌ±äÌ†µÌ±äÌ†µÌ±ä{Ì†µÌ∞±Ì†µÌ∞±Ì†µÌ∞±Ì†µÌ∞±|Ì†µÌ∞≤Ì†µÌ∞≤Ì†µÌ∞≤Ì†µÌ∞≤} . It is given as if every symbol was generated by memoryless channel W, equivalently. Errors occurred during QKD are commonly considered as uncorrelated and symmetric. Thus, the memoryless channel W can be seen as a binary symmetric channel (BSC). The crossover probability p of the BSC is generally supposed as given.

The problem is how a message M is encoded. This problem of reconciliation can be treated as well-known Slepian-Wolf coding, which is a way of encoding two lossless compressed correlated sources [9]. The Slepian-Wolf bound states that (Ì†µÌ±ãÌ†µÌ±ãÌ†µÌ±ãÌ†µÌ±ãÌ†µÌ±õÌ†µÌ±õÌ†µÌ±õÌ†µÌ±õ, Ì†µÌ±åÌ†µÌ±åÌ†µÌ±åÌ†µÌ±åÌ†µÌ±õÌ†µÌ±õÌ†µÌ±õÌ†µÌ±õ) can be compressed into more than Ì†µÌ±õÌ†µÌ±õÌ†µÌ±õÌ†µÌ±õÌ†µÌ±õÌ†µÌ±õÌ†µÌ±õÌ†µÌ±õ(Ì†µÌ±ãÌ†µÌ±ãÌ†µÌ±ãÌ†µÌ±ã|Ì†µÌ±åÌ†µÌ±åÌ†µÌ±åÌ†µÌ±å) bits without information loss. This is the minimum information required to agree on a secret key. In practice, codewords will be encoded with a rate Ì†µÌ±ìÌ†µÌ±ìÌ†µÌ±ìÌ†µÌ±ìÌ†µÌ±õÌ†µÌ±õÌ†µÌ±õÌ†µÌ±õ(Ì†µÌ±ãÌ†µÌ±ãÌ†µÌ±ãÌ†µÌ±ã|Ì†µÌ±åÌ†µÌ±åÌ†µÌ±åÌ†µÌ±å) , where Ì†µÌ±ìÌ†µÌ±ìÌ†µÌ±ìÌ†µÌ±ì is the reconciliation efficiency. Therefore, efficiency is defined as

